<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="CourseWork">

  <title>Course Work</title>

  <subsection xml:id="listening-responses">
    <title>Listening Responses</title>

    <p>
      These are designed to help you develop a critical ear for the familiar music that surrounds you
      and (perhaps) unfamiliar music you encounter in class.
    </p>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="in-class-activities">
    <title>In-Class Activities</title>

    <p>
      These are designed to apply what you are learning at a moment's notice.
      They cannot be done outside class time.
    </p>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="assignments">
    <title>Assignments</title>

    <p>
      Each one of these assignments are designed as part of the workflow for each project within each unit.
      They focus on technique, file management, and working with musical ideas.
      They must be handed in on time.
    </p>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="projects">
    <title>Projects</title>

    <p>
      <alert>Project #1: Sound Collage</alert>
      A short 1–2 minute piece that comes from sounds you've recorded, edited, and manipulated
      from the world around (outside in nature, in your home, at work, in the city, etc.).
      You must come up with an original title.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Project #2: POP!!</alert>
      A short 2–3 minute piece of music that uses standard instrumental layers, textures, and forms
      used in pop/rock music composed through software instruments using MIDI.
      You will be able to improve your score through following instructor feedback.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Project #3: Patchtastic</alert>
      For this project you will demonstrate your knowledge of synthesis, signal chain, sequencing,
      and generative operations in a virtual modular environment found in VCV Rack.
      You will be scored on patch organization and tidiness as well as the creative outcomes
      (some of which you will record).
      You will be able to improve your score through following instructor feedback.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Final Project: Composition</alert>
      This project is the culmination of everything you did throughout the semester.
      The piece should last at minimum 3 minutes.
      It will be played during class in front of your peers as part of the final exam.
    </p>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="Grading-Values">
    <title>Grading Values</title>
    
  
  <tabular halign="right">
  <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
    <cell>Category</cell>
    <cell>Weight</cell>
  </row>
